n of the twenty-first century. Drawing on previously unseen documents from NATO’s own archives, Simone Turchetti reveals how its investments were rooted in the alliance’s defense and surveillance needs, needs that led it to establish a program prioritizing environmental studies. A long-overlooked and effective diplomacy exercise, NATO’s “greening” at one point constituted the organization’s chief conduit for negotiating problematic relations between allies. But while Greening the Alliance explores this surprising coevolution of environmental monitoring and surveillance, tales of science advisers issuing instructions to bomb oil spills with napalm or Dr. Strangelove–like experts eager to divert the path of hurricanes with atomic weapons make it clear: the coexistence of these forces has not always been harmonious. Reflecting on this rich, complicated legacy in light of contemporary global challenges like climate change, Turchetti offers both an eye-opening history of international politics and environmental studies and a thoughtful assessment of NATO’s future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnvironmental protectionxResearchxHistory. 0aEnvironmental sciencesxHistoryx20th century. 0aEnvironmental sciencesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnvironmental sciencesxPolitical aspects. 0aResearchxHistoryx20th century. 0aResearchxHistoryy20th century. 0aResearchxPolitical aspects. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAtlantic Alliance.  aCold War.  aInternational Relations.  aatmospheric research.  aenvironmental diplomacy.  aenvironmental studies.  ameteorology.  aoceanography.  aremote sensing.  ascience diplomacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226595825423Coveruhttp